[[File:Janusz A Zajdel.jpg|thumbnail|Janusz A Zajdel]]
'''Janusz Andrzej Zajdel''' (15 August 1938 in [[Warsaw]] &ndash; 19 July 1985 in Warsaw) was a prominent [[Polish people|Polish]] [[science fiction authors|science fiction author]], second in popularity in Poland after [[Stanis<U+0142>aw Lem]].<ref name=tpe/><ref name=culture>{{cite web|url=http://culture.pl/pl/tworca/janusz-andrzej-zajdel|title=Janusz Andrzej Zajdel|work=Culture.pl|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> A major theme of his works was [[social science fiction]] and [[dystopia]]s. The main recurring theme in his works is a comparison of the readers' gloomy, hopeless situations to what may happen in a space environment if we carry totalitarian ideas and habits into space worlds: Red Space Republics or Space Labour Camps, or both. His heroes are desperately trying to find sense in world around them. His novels are recognized as classics of [[science fiction in Poland]]. 

His most famous works are the five social science fiction novels: ''[[Cylinder van Troffa]]'' ("Van Troff's cylinder"), 1980; ''[[Limes inferior]]'', 1982; ''[[Ca<U+0142>a prawda o planecie Ksi]]'' ("Complete Truth about planet Xi"), 1983; '' {{ill|pl|Wyj<U+015B>cie z cienia}}'' ("Out of the Shadow"), 1983 and ''[[Paradyzja]]'' ("Paradise, the World in Orbit"), 1984.<ref name=culture/> Polish [[science fiction fandom]] award was named after him (the [[Janusz A. Zajdel Award]]). He was a Trustee of [[World SF]].<ref name=tpe/>

==Biography==
Zajdel was born on 15 August 1938 in Warsaw.<ref name=culture/> He studied physics at the [[University of Warsaw]]. After graduation he worked for many years as an radiological engineer and an expert on [[nuclear physics]] at the Central Laboratory of Radiological Protection in Poland.<ref name=culture/> He became an active supporter of Polish [[Solidarnosc|Solidarity]] movement in the 1980s.<ref name=culture/> In his professional career he published a number of academic works, handbooks of safety regulations, as well as educational texts.<ref name=culture/><ref name=sfe/>

In his spare time he engaged in popularizing science through writing [[science fiction]].<ref name=culture/> Together with his brother he started a column in Polish magazine aimed at youth interested in science and engineering, '' {{ill|pl|M<U+0142>ody Technik}}'' (''Young Technician''), in which they proposed various futuristic gadgets.<ref name=culture/> His other stories soon appeared in several other Polish magazines.<ref name=culture/> His sf book writing career started in 1965 with the publication of a short story anthology ''Jad mantezji'' ("The Venom of Mantesia"), through the texts from ''M<U+0142>ody Technik'' as well as some others already appeared in another anthology a year earlier.<ref name=culture/><ref name=tpe/> By 1982 he had published four more collections: ''Przej<U+015B>cie przez lustro'' ("Crossing the Mirror"), 1975; ''Iluzyt'' (1976); ''Feniks'' ("Phoenix") (1981) and ''Ogon diab<U+0142>a'' ("Devil's Tail") (1982).<ref name=sfe/>

His first novel, ''Lalande 21185'', appeared in 1966, a year after his first short story anthology, and was geared towards young adults.<ref name=culture/> His first serious sf novel appears was '' {{ill|pl|Prawo do powrotu}}'' ("The Right to Return") (1975), but it is his novels from late 70s and early 80s, namely '[[Cylinder van Troffa]]'' ("Van Troff's cylinder"), 1980; ''[[Limes inferior]]'', 1982; ''[[Ca<U+0142>a prawda o planecie Ksi]]'' ("Complete Truth about planet Xi"), 1983; '' {{ill|pl|Wyj<U+015B>cie z cienia}}'' ("Out of the Shadow") and 1983 ''[[Paradyzja]]'' ("Paradise, the World in Orbit"), 1984that earned him his reputation as one of the most important writers of Polish science-fiction of this time.<ref name=culture/><ref name=sfe/>


He was an active member of the Polish and international [[science fiction fandom]], and a Trustee of [[World SF]].<ref name=culture/><ref name=tpe/>

He died of [[lung cancer]] after three years of fighting the disease.<ref name=tpe>{{cite book|author1=Frederik Pohl|author2=Elizabeth Anne Hull|title=Tales From The Planet Earth|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=jvBeJQw39RYC&pg=PA268|date=15 October 1986|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-0-312-78420-1|page=268}}</ref><ref name=culture/>

==Themes==
Zajdel's early works, from 60s and early 70s, can be located in the [[John W. Campbell|Cambellian]], [[classic science fiction]] genre, focusing on scientific inventions and their role in space exploration, alien contact or artificial intelligence.<ref name=culture/><ref name=sfe/> Quickly, however, his stories evolved to focus on the social aspects and often negative consequences of those inventions.<ref name=culture/> Increasingly visible theme in his works was the concern over dangers inherent in attempts to control the human society.<ref name=culture/> He is also condemning human ignorance, warning against [[xenophobia]], and asking philosophical questions about the nature of the universe, happiness and human destiny.<ref name=culture/> Zajdel's most important works are from his second period - late 70s and 80s - and represent the genres of [[social fiction|social]] and [[dystopian fiction]].<ref name=culture/> In his works, he envisions [[totalitarianism|totalitarian states]] and societies leaving under extreme forms of [[mass surveillance]].<ref name=culture/> 

His works are also recognized as being a critique of the totalitarian, communist state, a reality of his life in [[People's Republic of Poland]]. Science-fiction genre, with its outer-worldly, clearly fictional, and often [[allegorical]] setting and [[koalang|invented jargon]] was able to debate fundamentals of such systems with frankness that more mainstream literature would not be allowed to.<ref name=culture/> 

==Significance==
Zajdel has been described as the second science fiction writer in popularity in Poland after [[Stanis<U+0142>aw Lem]].<ref name=tpe/><ref name=culture/> He has also been described as the writer who replaced Lem as the as the "top Polish SF writer", after "Lem vacated [this position] earlier of his own volition".<ref name="GepfertKozubski2000">{{cite book|author1=El<U+017C>bieta Gepfert|author2=Grzegorz Kozubski|author3=Piotr W. Cholewa|title=Anthology: chosen by fate : Zajdel award winners|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=LMcZAQAAIAAJ|year=2000|publisher=<U+015A>l<U+0105>ski Klub Fantastyki|isbn=978-83-7054-142-2|page=8}}</ref>

He is recognized as an originator of the [[social science fiction]] genre in Polish science fiction, a genre also know as the (Polish) [[sociological fiction]] (''fantastyka socjologiczna'').<ref name=zajdelarto>{{cite web|url=http://zajdel.art.pl/janusz-a-zajdel/|title=Janusz A. Zajdel|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014|language=Polish}}</ref><ref name=culture/><ref name=sfe/> He has been an inspiration to a number of younger Polish science fiction authors such as [[Maciej Parowski]] and [[Marek Oramus]].<ref name=culture/> 

His works have been translated into Belorussian, Bulgarian, Czech, Esperanto, Finnish, German, Hungarian, Russian and Slovenian.<ref name=sfe>{{cite web|url=http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/zajdel_janusz_a|title=Authors : Zajdel, Janusz A : SFE : Science Fiction Encyclopedia|publisher=|accessdate=8 October 2014}}</ref> Almost none of his works have been translated into English; the only exception is the short story ''Wyj<U+0105>tkowo trudny teren'' ("Particularly Difficult Territory") that Zajdel wrote for the English language ''[[Tales from the Planet Earth]]'' anthology edited by [[Frederik Pohl]] and [[Elizabeth Anne Hull]].<ref name=sfe/>

==Awards and recognition==
In 1973 Zajdel received a honorary award Magnum Trophaeum from the ''M<U+0142>ody Technik'' (''Young Technician'') magazine for long-term cooperation: Zajdel's SF debut was the 1961 short story ''Tau Ceti'' (or ''Tau Wieloryba''<ref name=culture/>) published in ''M<U+0142>ody Technik''.<ref>Janusz A. Zajdel, ''List Po<U+017C>egnalny'', 1989, ISBN 8370011896, p. 6.</ref> In 1980 Zajdel received the award of the [[Polish Ministry of Culture and Arts]] for ''Van Troff's Cylinder''.<ref>Robert Klementowski, "Modelowe boksowanie ze <U+015B>wiatem: polska literatura fantastyczna na prze<U+0142>omie lat 70. i 80", 2003, ISBN	8373226087, p. 124</ref> Zajdel was twice recipient of the [[Golden Sepulka]] Award: for ''Limes Inferior'' (1982 novel; 1983 award) and ''Wyj<U+015B>cie z cienia'' ("Out of the Shadow") (1983 novel; 1984 award).<ref name=culture/>

In 1984 Polish fantasy and science fiction [[fandom]] (associated with the Polish SF convention [[Polcon]]) decided to establish an annual award, initially named ''Sfinks'' ("Sphynx"). Janusz A. Zajdel became the first winner of this award, for his 1984 novel ''Paradyzja''. He won the award in 1985, shortly after his death, at which time it was decided to rename the award after him, the [[Janusz A. Zajdel Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zajdel.art.pl/historia-nagrody/|title=Historia Nagrody|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014|language=Polish}}</ref><ref name=culture/>

[[Frederik Pohl]] dedicated the anthology ''[[Tales From The Planet Earth]]'' to Zajdel and [[A. Bertram Chandler]].<ref name="PohlHull1986">{{cite book|author1=Frederik Pohl|author2=Elizabeth Anne Hull|title=Tales From The Planet Earth|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=jvBeJQw39RYC|date=15 October 1986|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-0-312-78420-1}} p. v</ref> This book also contains the English translation of one of Zajdel's short stories, ''Particularly Difficult Territory''. It is his only work to have been translated into English to date.<ref name=sfe/>

==Bibliography==
In addition to the solo-authored works listed below, Zajdel stories also appeared collected in numerous anthologies of sf stories together with works of other authors.<ref name=culture/>

===Novels===
* ''[[Lalande 21185 (novel)|Lalande 21185]]'', 1966
* ''[[Prawo do powrotu]]'' ("Right of Return") ''[[Nasza Ksi<U+0119>garnia]]'', 1975
* ''[[Cylinder van Troffa]]'' ("Van Troff's cylinder"), 1980
* ''[[Limes inferior]]'', 1982
* ''[[Ca<U+0142>a prawda o planecie Ksi]]'' ("Complete Truth about planet Xi"), 1983
* ''[[Wyj<U+015B>cie z cienia]]'' ("Out of the Shadow"), 1983
* ''[[Paradyzja]]'' ("Paradise, the World in Orbit"), 1984
* ''[[Drugie spojrzenie na planet<U+0119> Ksi]]'' ("Second Look at Planet Xi"), posthumously finished by Marcin Kowalczyk, 2014

===Short story collections===
* ''Jad mantezji'' (Nasza Ksi<U+0119>garnia, 1965)
* ''Przej<U+015B>cie przez lustro'' (Iskry, 1975)
* ''Iluzyt'' (Nasza Ksi<U+0119>garnia, 1976)
* ''Feniks'' (Nasza Ksi<U+0119>garnia, 1981)
* ''Ogon diab<U+0142>a'' (KAW, 1982)
* ''Dok<U+0105>d jedzie ten tramwaj?'' ("Where is that tram going?"), 1988\
* ''Wy<U+017C>sze racje'' (Wydawnictwo Pozna<U+0144>skie, 1988)
* ''List po<U+017C>egnalny'' [includes outlines of unfinished novels) (Alfa, 1989)
* ''Relacja z pierwszej r<U+0119>ki'' (superNOWA, 2010)

